[2] USA (Louisiana)
Date: Wed 28 Mar 2018 5:10 PM CDT
Source: WWLTV [edited]
http://www.wwltv.com/article/news/health/several-babies-at-local-daycare-center-sick-with-chicken-pox/289-532925286


This long Easter weekend, several parents will be staying at home taking care of very sick children, rather than going to holiday festivities.

Parents with babies at the Cub Corner Preschool in Lakeview are seeing something rare - a cluster of children, younger than a year old, with chicken pox.

"It's very common. It's very contagious, and it's very easily spread from one person to the next," said Dr. Michael Wasserman.

Dr. Wasserman is a pediatrician at Oschner for Children and he is not seeing it in his practice. The state Health Department isn't seeing other places with clusters either, but a letter to the parents from the preschool confirms 5 cases. Some parents believe there are now 8. Pediatricians recommend children get the chicken pox vaccine at 1 year and at 4 years of age. In the 1st year of life, they have some immunity passed on from mothers.

But on [Wed 28 Mar 2018], the Louisiana Department of Health and Hospitals sent a letter to the parents, recommending exposed children, at least 6 months of age and older, get the vaccine. Dr. Wasserman agrees with the state recommendation.

"Would you rather get it (chicken pox) from the immunization, which is controlled, or would you rather get something that is wild and uncontrolled, and could make you much sicker with complications?"

Dr. Wasserman is concerned that children with 30--100 lesions will be at risk for getting staph infection in them, the kind that is resistant to antibiotics. Both he and state doctors recommend children get on the prescription antiviral acyclovir the 1st day the rash breaks out and keep the rash extra clean.

"Chicken pox has a lot of misery associated with it, and so the treatments include, medication for itch such as Benadryl, or one of the other oral antihistamines, Zyrtec or Claritin. You can put Calamine lotion. You can use Aveeno oatmeal baths, and you clean the heck out of the kids," said Dr. Wasserman.

The preschool says a child may have been misdiagnosed with a different infection (impetigo) before coming in. Also doctors remind adults that if they have the shingles, that can be passed on as chicken pox to people who have not been vaccinated or who have never had a case.

[Byline: Meg Farris]

